<p>Have no fear, pushd and popd are here! Yep, command line directory systems have stacks too (obviously).</p>

<p>If youâ€™re not familiar with what a stack is, or how it works, itâ€™s simply a data structure, like a stack of plates. You place a plate on top of the stack, you take the plate off the stack, you can get to the next plate, so and and so forth. Itâ€™s a data structure seen time and time again throughout computer science, you can read more about it on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stack_(abstract_data_type)">Wikipedia</a>.</p>

<p>If your system supports directory stacks, each directory you switch to will be pushed onto the stack. This means if you want to quickly return back to your previous directory, you can pop it back off the stack! These stacks can go on and on, theyâ€™re not limited to just a single directory change either!</p>

